A push is when you actively reach out to customers to understand their needs and desires. This can be done through surveys, interviews, or focus groups. The goal is to gather information about what customers want and need in a product or service.

A pull, on the other hand, is when you observe customers in their natural environment to see how they interact with your product or service. This can be done through ethnographic research, usability testing, or customer feedback. The goal is to understand how customers actually use your product or service and what their pain points are.

In the context of jobs-to-be-done (JTBD), a push is when you try to understand the job that a customer is trying to accomplish, while a pull is when you observe how customers actually go about accomplishing that job. To create an LCD control system using a potentiometer and temperature sensor with Arduino, you can follow these steps:

1. Connect the LM35 temperature sensor to your Arduino board. The sensor's VCC and GND pins should be connected to the Arduino's power and ground, respectively. The analog output pin of the LM35 should be connected to the analog input pin A0 of the Arduino [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

2. Connect the 10K Ohm potentiometer to control the brightness of the LCD panel. The first pin of the potentiometer should be connected to +VCC, the second pin to pin 3 of the LCD, and the third pin to GND [[3](https://www.hackatronic.com/arduino-with-temperature-sensor-interfacing-lcd-and-lm35/)].

3. Install the necessary libraries in the Arduino IDE. Go to Tools > Manage Libraries, search for "LiquidCrystal I2C", and install the LiquidCrystal_I2C library by Frank de Brabander [[2](https://arduinogetstarted.com/tutorials/arduino-display-temperature-from-lm35-sensor-on-lcd)].

4. Upload the code to your Arduino board. The error message is telling you that the `using enum` feature requires C++20 or later. By default, Visual Studio uses an older version of the C++ standard.

To enable C++20 in Visual Studio, you can follow these steps:

1. Right-click on your project in the Solution Explorer.
2. Select "Properties" from the context menu.
3. In the Properties window, go to "Configuration Properties" > "C/C++" > "Language".
4. Set the "C++ Language Standard" option to "ISO C++20 Standard (/std:c++20)".
5. Click "Apply" and then "OK" to save the changes.
